# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1979-vuelta-a-espana
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/1979-vuelta-a-espana] The 34th Edition ***Vuelta a España*** (Tour of Spain), a long-distance bicycle stage race and one of the three grand tours, was held from 24 April to 13 May 1979.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/1979-vuelta-a-espana] It consisted of 19 stages covering a total of 3,373 km (2,096 mi), and was won by Joop Zoetemelk of the Miko–Mercier cycling team.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/1979-vuelta-a-espana] Zoetemelk won two of the three ITT's and Fons De Wolf won the other.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/1979-vuelta-a-espana] De Wolf also won the points classification as well as five stages, but Zoetemelk won the race with a comfortable lead ahead of Spanish climbing specialist Francisco Galdós and Michel Pollentier.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/1979-vuelta-a-espana] Felipe Yáñez won the mountains classification.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] A **diacritic** (also **diacritical mark**, **diacritical point**, **diacritical sign**, or **accent**) is a glyph added to a letter or to a basic glyph.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The term derives from the Ancient Greek διακριτικός (*diakritikós*, "distinguishing"), from διακρίνω (*diakrínō*, "to distinguish").
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The word *diacritic* is a noun, though it is sometimes used in an attributive sense, whereas *diacritical* is only an adjective.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Some diacritics, such as the acute ⟨ó⟩, grave ⟨ò⟩, and circumflex ⟨ô⟩ (all shown above an 'o'), are often called *accents*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Diacritics may appear above or below a letter or in some other position such as within the letter or between two letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The main use of diacritics in Latin script is to change the sound-values of the letters to which they are added.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Historically, English has used the diaeresis diacritic to indicate the correct pronunciation of ambiguous words, such as "coöperate", without which the <oo> letter sequence could be misinterpreted to be pronounced /ˈkuːpəreɪt/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Most other words with diacritics in English are borrowings from languages such as French to better preserve the spelling, such as the diaeresis on *naïve* and *Noël*, the acute from *café*, the circumflex in the word *crêpe*, and the cedille in *façade*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] All these diacritics, however, are frequently omitted in writing, and English is the only major modern European language that does not have diacritics in common usage.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In Latin-script alphabets in other languages diacritics may distinguish between homonyms, such as the French *là* ("there") versus *la* ("the"), which are both pronounced /la/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In Gaelic type, a dot over a consonant indicates lenition of the consonant in question.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In other writing systems, diacritics may perform other functions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Vowel pointing systems, namely the Arabic harakat and the Hebrew niqqud systems, indicate vowels that are not conveyed by the basic alphabet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The Indic virama ( ् etc.) and the Arabic sukūn ( ـْـ ) mark the absence of vowels.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Other uses include the Early Cyrillic titlo stroke ( ◌҃ ) and the Hebrew gershayim ( ״ ), which, respectively, mark abbreviations or acronyms, and Greek diacritical marks, which showed that letters of the alphabet were being used as numerals.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In Vietnamese and the Hanyu Pinyin official romanization system for Mandarin in China, diacritics are used to mark the tones of the syllables in which the marked vowels occur.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In orthography and collation, a letter modified by a diacritic may be treated either as a new, distinct letter or as a letter–diacritic combination.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] This varies from language to language and may vary from case to case within a language.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In some cases, letters are used as "in-line diacritics", with the same function as ancillary glyphs, in that they modify the sound of the letter preceding them, as in the case of the "h" in the English pronunciation of "sh" and "th".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Such letter combinations are sometimes even collated as a single distinct letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For example, the spelling sch was traditionally often treated as a separate letter in German.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Words with that spelling were listed after all other words spelled with s in card catalogs in the Vienna public libraries, for example (before digitization).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The tilde, dot, comma, titlo, apostrophe, bar, and colon are sometimes diacritical marks, but also have other uses.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Not all diacritics occur adjacent to the letter they modify.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In the Wali language of Ghana, for example, an apostrophe indicates a change of vowel quality, but occurs at the beginning of the word, as in the dialects *’Bulengee* and *’Dolimi*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Because of vowel harmony, all vowels in a word are affected, so the scope of the diacritic is the entire word.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In abugida scripts, like those used to write Hindi and Thai, diacritics indicate vowels, and may occur above, below, before, after, or around the consonant letter they modify.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The tittle (dot) on the letter ⟨i⟩ or the letter ⟨j⟩, of the Latin alphabet originated as a diacritic to clearly distinguish ⟨i⟩ from the minims (downstrokes) of adjacent letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] It first appeared in the 11th century in the sequence *ii* (as in *ingeníí*), then spread to *i* adjacent to *m, n, u*, and finally to all lowercase *i*s.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The ⟨j⟩, originally a variant of *i*, inherited the tittle.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The shape of the diacritic developed from initially resembling today's acute accent to a long flourish by the 15th century.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] With the advent of Roman type it was reduced to the round dot we have today.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Several languages of eastern Europe use diacritics on both consonants and vowels, whereas in western Europe digraphs are more often used to change consonant sounds.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Most languages in Europe use diacritics on vowels, aside from English where there are typically none (with some exceptions).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The diacritics **〮** and **〯** , known as Bangjeom (방점; 傍點), were used to mark pitch accents in Hangul for Middle Korean.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] They were written to the left of a syllable in vertical writing and above a syllable in horizontal writing.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In addition to the above vowel marks, transliteration of Syriac sometimes includes *ə*, *e̊* or superscript *e* (or often nothing at all) to represent an original Aramaic schwa that became lost later on at some point in the development of Syriac.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Some transliteration schemes find its inclusion necessary for showing spirantization or for historical reasons.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Some non-alphabetic scripts also employ symbols that function essentially as diacritics.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Different languages use different rules to put diacritic characters in alphabetical order.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For example, French and Portuguese treat letters with diacritical marks the same as the underlying letter for purposes of ordering and dictionaries.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The Scandinavian languages and the Finnish language, by contrast, treat the characters with diacritics ⟨å⟩, ⟨ä⟩, and ⟨ö⟩ as distinct letters of the alphabet, and sort them after ⟨z⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Usually ⟨ä⟩ (a-umlaut) and ⟨ö⟩ (o-umlaut) [used in Swedish and Finnish] are sorted as equivalent to ⟨æ⟩ (ash) and ⟨ø⟩ (o-slash) [used in Danish and Norwegian].
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Also, *aa*, when used as an alternative spelling to ⟨å⟩, is sorted as such.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Other letters modified by diacritics are treated as variants of the underlying letter, with the exception that ⟨ü⟩ is frequently sorted as ⟨y⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Languages that treat accented letters as variants of the underlying letter usually alphabetize words with such symbols immediately after similar unmarked words.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For instance, in German where two words differ only by an umlaut, the word without it is sorted first in German dictionaries (e.g.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] *schon* and then *schön*, or *fallen* and then *fällen*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] However, when names are concerned (e.g. in phone books or in author catalogues in libraries), umlauts are often treated as combinations of the vowel with a suffixed ⟨e⟩; Austrian phone books now treat characters with umlauts as separate letters (immediately following the underlying vowel).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In Spanish, the grapheme ⟨ñ⟩ is considered a distinct letter, different from ⟨n⟩ and collated between ⟨n⟩ and ⟨o⟩, as it denotes a different sound from that of a plain ⟨n⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] But the accented vowels ⟨á⟩, ⟨é⟩, ⟨í⟩, ⟨ó⟩, ⟨ú⟩ are not separated from the unaccented vowels ⟨a⟩, ⟨e⟩, ⟨i⟩, ⟨o⟩, ⟨u⟩, as the acute accent in Spanish only modifies stress within the word or denotes a distinction between homonyms, and does not modify the sound of a letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For a comprehensive list of the collating orders in various languages, see Collating sequence.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Modern computer technology was developed mostly in countries that speak Western European languages (particularly English), and many early binary encodings were developed with a bias favoring English—a language written without diacritical marks.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] With computer memory and computer storage at premium, early character sets were limited to the Latin alphabet, the ten digits and a few punctuation marks and conventional symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII), first published in 1963, encoded just 95 printable characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] It included just four free-standing diacritics—acute, grave, circumflex and tilde—which were to be used by backspacing and overprinting the base letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The ISO/IEC 646 standard (1967) defined national variations that replace some American graphemes with precomposed characters (such as ⟨é⟩, ⟨è⟩ and ⟨ë⟩), according to language—but remained limited to 95 printable characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Unicode was conceived to solve this problem by assigning every known character its own code; if this code is known, most modern computer systems provide a method to input it.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For historical reasons, almost all the letter-with-accent combinations used in European languages were given unique code points and these are called precomposed characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] For other languages, it is usually necessary to use a combining character diacritic together with the desired base letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Unfortunately, even as of 2024, many applications and web browsers remain unable to operate the combining diacritic concept properly.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Depending on the keyboard layout and keyboard mapping, it is more or less easy to enter letters with diacritics on computers and typewriters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] Keyboards used in countries where letters with diacritics are the norm, have keys engraved with the relevant symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] In other cases, such as when the US international or UK extended mappings are used, the accented letter is created by first pressing the key with the diacritic mark, followed by the letter to place it on.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] This method is known as the dead key technique, as it produces no output of its own but modifies the output of the key pressed after it.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p01] The following languages have letters with diacritics that are orthographically distinct from those without diacritics.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] English is one of the few European languages that does not have many words that contain diacritical marks.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Instead, digraphs are the main way the Modern English alphabet adapts the Latin to its phonemes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Exceptions are unassimilated foreign loanwords, including borrowings from French (and, increasingly, Spanish, like *jalapeño* and *piñata*); however, the diacritic is also sometimes omitted from such words.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Loanwords that frequently appear with the diacritic in English include *café*, *résumé* or *resumé* (a usage that helps distinguish it from the verb *resume*), *soufflé*, and *naïveté* (see *English terms with diacritical marks*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] English speakers and writers once used the diaeresis more often than now in words such as *coöperation* (from Fr.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] *zoologia*), and *seeër* (now more commonly *see-er*or simply*seer*) as a way of indicating that adjacent vowels belonged to separate syllables, but this practice has become far less common.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] *The New Yorker* magazine is a major publication that continues to use the diaeresis in place of a hyphen for clarity and economy of space.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] A few English words, often when used out of context, especially in isolation, can only be distinguished from other words of the same spelling by using a diacritic or modified letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] The acute and grave accents are occasionally used in poetry and lyrics: the acute to indicate stress overtly where it might be ambiguous (*rébel* vs.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] *rebél*) or nonstandard for metrical reasons (*caléndar*), the grave to indicate that an ordinarily silent or elided syllable is pronounced (*warnèd,* *parlìament*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] In certain personal names such as *Renée* and *Zoë*, often two spellings exist, and the person's own preference will be known only to those close to them.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] They also appear in some worldwide company names and/or trademarks, such as *Nestlé* and *Citroën*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] The following languages have letter-diacritic combinations that are not considered independent letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Several languages that are not written with the Roman alphabet are transliterated, or romanized, using diacritics.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Possibly the greatest number of combining diacritics *required* to compose a valid character in any Unicode language is 8, for the "well-known grapheme cluster in Tibetan and Ranjana scripts" or *HAKṢHMALAWARAYAṀ*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/diacritical-mark-p02] Some users have explored the limits of rendering in web browsers and other software by "decorating" words with excessive nonsensical diacritics per character to produce so-called Zalgo text.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The **Greek alphabet** has been used to write the Greek language since the late 9th or early 8th century BC.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] It was derived from the earlier Phoenician alphabet, and is the earliest known alphabetic script to systematically write vowels as well as consonants.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greek alphabet is the ancestor of several scripts, such as the Latin, Gothic, Coptic, and Cyrillic scripts.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Throughout antiquity, Greek had only a single uppercase form of each letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] It was written without diacritics and with little punctuation.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] By the 9th century, Byzantine scribes had begun to employ the lowercase form, which they derived from the cursive styles of the uppercase letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Sound values and conventional transcriptions for some of the letters differ between Ancient and Modern Greek usage because the pronunciation of Greek has changed significantly between the 5th century BC and the present.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Additionally, Modern and Ancient Greek now use different diacritics, with ancient Greek using the polytonic orthography and modern Greek keeping only the stress accent (acute) and the diaeresis.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Apart from its use in writing the Greek language, in both its ancient and its modern forms, the Greek alphabet today also serves as a source of international technical symbols and labels in many domains of mathematics, science, and other fields.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In both Ancient and Modern Greek, the letters of the Greek alphabet have fairly stable and consistent symbol-to-sound mappings, making pronunciation of words largely predictable.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Ancient Greek spelling was generally near-phonemic.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For a number of letters, sound values differ considerably between Ancient and Modern Greek, because their pronunciation has followed a set of systematic phonological shifts that affected the language in its post-classical stages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] These are not the sounds they made in classical Attic Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In classical Attic Greek, these three letters were always aspirated consonants, pronounced exactly like tau, pi, and kappa respectively, only with a blast of air following the actual consonant sound.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter Λ is almost universally known today as *lambda* (λάμβδα) except in Modern Greek and in Unicode, where it is *lamda* (λάμδα), and the most common name for it during the Greek Classical Period (510–323 BC) appears to have been *labda* (λάβδα), without the μ.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter sigma ⟨Σ⟩ has two different lowercase forms in its standard variant, with ⟨ς⟩ being used in word-final position and ⟨σ⟩ elsewhere.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In some 19th-century typesetting, ⟨ς⟩ was also used word-medially at the end of a compound morpheme, e.g. δυςκατανοήτων, marking the morpheme boundary between δυς-κατανοήτων ('difficult to understand'); modern standard practice is to spell δυσκατανοήτων with a non-final sigma.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter omega ⟨ω⟩ is normally taught to English speakers as [oʊ], the long o as in English *go*, in order to more clearly distinguish it from omicron ⟨ο⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This is not the sound it actually made in classical Attic Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Among consonant letters, all letters that denoted voiced plosive consonants (/b, d, g/) and aspirated plosives (/pʰ, tʰ, kʰ/) in Ancient Greek stand for corresponding fricative sounds in Modern Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Among the vowel letters, Modern Greek sound values reflect the radical simplification of the vowel system of post-classical Greek, merging multiple formerly distinct vowel phonemes into a much smaller number.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This leads to several groups of vowel letters denoting identical sounds today.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Modern Greek orthography remains true to the historical spellings in most of these cases.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] As a consequence, the spellings of words in Modern Greek are often not predictable from the pronunciation alone, while the reverse mapping, from spelling to pronunciation, is usually regular and predictable.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Modern Greek speakers typically use the same, modern symbol–sound mappings in reading Greek of all historical stages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In other countries, students of Ancient Greek may use a variety of conventional approximations of the historical sound system in pronouncing Ancient Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Several letter combinations have special conventional sound values different from those of their single components.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Among them are several digraphs of vowel letters that formerly represented diphthongs but are now monophthongized.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition to the four mentioned above (⟨ει, οι, υι⟩, pronounced /i/ and ⟨αι⟩, pronounced /e/), there is also ⟨ηι, ωι⟩, and ⟨ου⟩, pronounced /u/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Ancient Greek diphthongs ⟨αυ⟩, ⟨ευ⟩ and ⟨ηυ⟩ are pronounced [av], [ev] and [iv] in Modern Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In some environments, they are devoiced to [af], [ef] and [if].
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Modern Greek consonant combinations ⟨μπ⟩ and ⟨ντ⟩ stand for [b] and [d] (or [mb] and [nd]); ⟨τζ⟩ stands for [d͡z] and ⟨τσ⟩ stands for [t͡s].
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition, both in Ancient and Modern Greek, the letter ⟨γ⟩, before another velar consonant, stands for the velar nasal [ŋ]; thus ⟨γγ⟩ and ⟨γκ⟩ are pronounced like English ⟨ng⟩ like in the word finger (not like in the word thing).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In analogy to ⟨μπ⟩ and ⟨ντ⟩, ⟨γκ⟩ is also used to stand for [g] before vowels [a], [o] and [u], and [ɟ] before [e] and [i].
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] There are also the combinations ⟨γχ⟩ and ⟨γξ⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The smooth breathing marks the absence of an initial /h/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the polytonic orthography traditionally used for ancient Greek and katharevousa, the stressed vowel of each word carries one of three accent marks: either the acute accent (ά), the grave accent (ὰ), or the circumflex accent (α̃ or α̑).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] These signs were originally designed to mark different forms of the phonological pitch accent in Ancient Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] By the time their use became conventional and obligatory in Greek writing, in late antiquity, pitch accent was evolving into a single stress accent, and thus the three signs have not corresponded to a phonological distinction in actual speech ever since.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In addition to the accent marks, every word-initial vowel must carry either of two so-called "breathing marks": the rough breathing (ἁ), marking an /h/ sound at the beginning of a word, or the smooth breathing (ἀ), marking its absence.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter rho (ρ), although not a vowel, also carries rough breathing in a word-initial position.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] If a rho was geminated within a word, the first ρ always had the smooth breathing and the second the rough breathing (ῤῥ) leading to the transliteration *rrh*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The vowel letters ⟨α, η, ω⟩ carry an additional diacritic in certain words, the so-called iota subscript, which has the shape of a small vertical stroke or a miniature ⟨ι⟩ below the letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This iota represents the former offglide of what were originally long diphthongs, ⟨ᾱι, ηι, ωι⟩ (i.e. /aːi, ɛːi, ɔːi/), which became monophthongized during antiquity.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Another diacritic used in Greek is the diaeresis (*¨*), indicating a hiatus.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This system of diacritics was first developed by the scholar Aristophanes of Byzantium (c.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] 185/180 BC), who worked at the Musaeum in Alexandria during the 3rd century BC.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Aristophanes of Byzantium also was the first to divide poems into lines, rather than writing them like prose, and also introduced a series of signs for textual criticism.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In 1982, a new, simplified orthography, known as "monotonic", was adopted for official use in Modern Greek by the Greek state.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The polytonic system is still conventionally used for writing Ancient Greek, while in some book printing and generally in the usage of conservative writers it can still also be found in use for Modern Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Although it is not a diacritic, the comma has a similar function as a silent letter in a handful of Greek words, principally distinguishing ό,τι (*ó,ti*, 'whatever') from ότι (*óti*, 'that').
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] There are many different methods of rendering Greek text or Greek names in the Latin script.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The form in which classical Greek names are conventionally rendered in English goes back to the way Greek loanwords were incorporated into Latin in antiquity.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In this system, ⟨κ⟩ is replaced with ⟨c⟩, the diphthongs ⟨αι⟩ and ⟨οι⟩ are rendered as ⟨ae⟩ and ⟨oe⟩ (or ⟨æ,œ⟩); and ⟨ει⟩ and ⟨ου⟩ are simplified to ⟨i⟩ and ⟨u⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Smooth breathing marks are usually ignored and rough breathing marks are usually rendered as the letter ⟨h⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In modern scholarly transliteration of Ancient Greek, ⟨κ⟩ will usually be rendered as ⟨k⟩, and the vowel combinations ⟨αι, οι, ει, ου⟩ as ⟨ai, oi, ei, ou⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letters ⟨θ⟩ and ⟨φ⟩ are generally rendered as ⟨th⟩ and ⟨ph⟩; ⟨χ⟩ as either ⟨ch⟩ or ⟨kh⟩; and word-initial ⟨ρ⟩ as ⟨rh⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Standardized formal transcription systems have been defined by the International Organization for Standardization (as ISO 843), by the United Nations Group of Experts on Geographical Names, by the Library of Congress, and others.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] During the Mycenaean period, between roughly the 16th and 12th centuries BC, a script called Linear B was used to write the earliest attested form of the Greek language, known as Mycenaean Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This writing system, unrelated to the Greek alphabet, last appeared in the 13th century BC.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Inscription written in the Greek alphabet begin to emerge from the 8th century BC onward.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] While early samples of the Greek alphabet date from at least 775 BC, the oldest known substantial and comprehensible inscriptions, such as those on the Dipylon vase, the cup of Nestor, and cup of Acesander, date from c.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] It is accepted that the introduction of the alphabet occurred some time prior to these inscriptions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] While earlier dates have been proposed, the Greek alphabet is commonly held to have originated some time in the late 9th or early 8th century BC, conventionally around 800 BC.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The period between the use of the two writing systems, Linear B and the Greek alphabet, during which no Greek texts are attested, is known as the Greek Dark Ages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greeks adopted the alphabet from the earlier Phoenician alphabet, one of the closely related scripts used for the West Semitic languages, calling it Φοινικήια γράμματα 'Phoenician letters'.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] However, the Phoenician alphabet was limited to consonants.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] When it was adopted for writing Greek, certain consonants were adapted in order to express vowels.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The use of both vowels and consonants makes Greek the first alphabet in the narrow sense, as distinguished from the abjads used in Semitic languages, which have letters only for consonants.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek initially took over all of the 22 letters of Phoenician.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] A doublet of *waw* was also borrowed as a consonant for [w] (Ϝ, *digamma*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Eventually, a seventh vowel letter for the long /ɔː/ (Ω, *omega*) was introduced.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek also introduced three new consonant letters for its aspirated plosive sounds and consonant clusters: Φ (*phi*) for /pʰ/, Χ (*chi*) for /kʰ/ and Ψ (*psi*) for /ps/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In western Greek variants, Χ was instead used for /ks/ and Ψ for /kʰ/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The origin of these letters is a matter of some debate.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek was originally written predominantly from right to left, just like Phoenician, but scribes could freely alternate between directions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For a time, a writing style with alternating right-to-left and left-to-right lines (called *boustrophedon*, literally 'ox-turning', after the manner of an ox ploughing a field) was common, until in the classical period the left-to-right writing direction became the norm.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Individual letter shapes were mirrored depending on the writing direction of the current line.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] There were initially numerous local (epichoric) variants of the Greek alphabet, which differed in the use and non-use of the additional vowel and consonant symbols and several other features.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Epichoric alphabets are commonly divided into four major types according to their different treatments of additional consonant letters for the aspirated consonants (/pʰ, kʰ/) and consonant clusters (/ks, ps/) of Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] These four types are often conventionally labelled as "green", "red", "light blue" and "dark blue" types, based on a colour-coded map in a seminal 19th-century work on the topic, *Studien zur Geschichte des griechischen Alphabets* by Adolf Kirchhoff (1867).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The "green" (or southern) type is the most archaic and closest to the Phoenician.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The "red" (or western) type is the one that was later transmitted to the West and became the ancestor of the Latin alphabet, and bears some crucial features characteristic of that later development.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The "blue" (or eastern) type is the one from which the later standard Greek alphabet emerged.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Athens used a local form of the "light blue" alphabet type until the end of the 5th century BC, which lacked the letters Ξ and Ψ as well as the vowel symbols Η and Ω.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the Old Attic alphabet, ΧΣ stood for /ks/ and ΦΣ for /ps/. Ε was used for all three sounds /e, eː, ɛː/ (correspondinɡ to classical Ε, ΕΙ, Η), and Ο was used for all of /o, oː, ɔː/ (corresponding to classical Ο, ΟΥ, Ω).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter Η (heta) was used for the consonant /h/.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Some variant local letter forms were also characteristic of Athenian writing, some of which were shared with the neighboring (but otherwise "red") alphabet of Euboia: a form of Λ that resembled a Latin *L* () and a form of Σ that resembled a Latin *S* ().
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The classical twenty-four-letter alphabet that is now used to represent the Greek language was originally the local alphabet of Ionia.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] By the late 5th century BC, it was commonly used by many Athenians.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] 403 BC, at the suggestion of the archon Eucleides, the Athenian Assembly formally abandoned the Old Attic alphabet and adopted the Ionian alphabet as part of the democratic reforms after the overthrow of the Thirty Tyrants.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Because of Eucleides's role in suggesting the idea to adopt the Ionian alphabet, the standard twenty-four-letter Greek alphabet is sometimes known as the "Eucleidean alphabet".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Roughly thirty years later, the Eucleidean alphabet was adopted in Boeotia and it may have been adopted a few years previously in Macedonia.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] By the end of the 4th century BC, it had displaced local alphabets across the Greek-speaking world to become the standard form of the Greek alphabet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] When the Greeks adopted the Phoenician alphabet, they took over not only the letter shapes and sound values but also the names by which the sequence of the alphabet could be recited and memorized.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In Phoenician, each letter name was a word that began with the sound represented by that letter; thus *ʾaleph*, the word for "ox", was used as the name for the glottal stop /ʔ/, *bet*, or "house", for the /b/ sound, and so on.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] When the letters were adopted by the Greeks, most of the Phoenician names were maintained or modified slightly to fit Greek phonology; thus, *ʾaleph, bet, gimel* became *alpha, beta, gamma*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Greek names of the following letters are more or less straightforward continuations of their Phoenician antecedents.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The name of lambda is attested in early sources as λάβδα besides λάμβδα; in Modern Greek the spelling is often λάμδα, reflecting pronunciation.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Similarly, iota is sometimes spelled γιώτα in Modern Greek ([ʝ] is conventionally transcribed ⟨γ{ι,η,υ,ει,οι}⟩ word-initially and intervocalically before back vowels and /a/).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the tables below, the Greek names of all letters are given in their traditional polytonic spelling; in modern practice, like with all other words, they are usually spelled in the simplified monotonic system.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the cases of the three historical sibilant letters below, the correspondence between Phoenician and Ancient Greek is less clear, with apparent mismatches both in letter names and sound values.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The early history of these letters (and the fourth sibilant letter, obsolete san) has been a matter of some debate.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Here too, the changes in the pronunciation of the letter names between Ancient and Modern Greek are regular.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the following group of consonant letters, the older forms of the names in Ancient Greek were spelled with -εῖ, indicating an original pronunciation with *-ē*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In Modern Greek these names are spelled with -ι.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The following group of vowel letters were originally called simply by their sound values as long vowels: ē, ō, ū, and ɔ.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Their modern names contain adjectival qualifiers that were added during the Byzantine period, to distinguish between letters that had become confusable.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Thus, the letters ⟨ο⟩ and ⟨ω⟩, pronounced identically by this time, were called *o mikron* ("small o") and *o mega* ("big o").
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The letter ⟨ε⟩ was called *e psilon* ("plain e") to distinguish it from the identically pronounced digraph ⟨αι⟩, while, similarly, ⟨υ⟩, which at this time was pronounced [y], was called *y psilon* ("plain y") to distinguish it from the identically pronounced digraph ⟨οι⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Some dialects of the Aegean and Cypriot have retained long consonants and pronounce [ˈɣamːa] and [ˈkapʰa]; also, ήτα has come to be pronounced [ˈitʰa] in Cypriot.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Like Latin and other alphabetic scripts, Greek originally had only a single form of each letter, without a distinction between uppercase and lowercase.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This distinction is an innovation of the modern era, drawing on different lines of development of the letter shapes in earlier handwriting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The oldest forms of the letters in antiquity are majuscule forms.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Besides the upright, straight inscriptional forms (capitals) found in stone carvings or incised pottery, more fluent writing styles adapted for handwriting on soft materials were also developed during antiquity.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Such handwriting has been preserved especially from papyrus manuscripts in Egypt since the Hellenistic period.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Ancient handwriting developed two distinct styles: uncial writing, with carefully drawn, rounded block letters of about equal size, used as a book hand for carefully produced literary and religious manuscripts, and cursive writing, used for everyday purposes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The cursive forms approached the style of lowercase letter forms, with ascenders and descenders, as well as many connecting lines and ligatures between letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the 9th and 10th centuries, uncial book hands were replaced with a new, more compact writing style, with letter forms partly adapted from the earlier cursive.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This minuscule style remained the dominant form of handwritten Greek into the modern era.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] During the Renaissance, western printers adopted the minuscule letter forms as lowercase printed typefaces, while modeling uppercase letters on the ancient inscriptional forms.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The orthographic practice of using the letter case distinction for marking proper names, titles, etc. developed in parallel to the practice in Latin and other western languages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Apart from the daughter alphabets listed above, which were adapted from Greek but developed into separate writing systems, the Greek alphabet has also been adopted at various times and in various places to write other languages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For some of them, additional letters were introduced.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek symbols are used as symbols in mathematics, physics and other sciences.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Many symbols have traditional uses, such as lower case epsilon (ε) for an arbitrarily small positive number, lower case pi (π) for the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter, capital sigma (Σ) for summation, and lower case sigma (σ) for standard deviation.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For many years the Greek alphabet was used by the World Meteorological Organization for naming North Atlantic hurricanes if a season was so active that it exhausted the regular list of storm names.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This happened during the 2005 season (when Alpha through Zeta were used), and the 2020 season (when Alpha through Iota were used), after which the practice was discontinued.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In May 2021 the World Health Organization announced that the variants of SARS-CoV-2 of the virus would be named using letters of the Greek alphabet to avoid stigma and simplify communications for non-scientific audiences.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek letters are used to denote the brighter stars within each of the eighty-eight constellations.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In most constellations, the brightest star is designated Alpha and the next brightest Beta etc.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For example, the brightest star in the constellation of Centaurus is known as Alpha Centauri.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For historical reasons, the Greek designations of some constellations begin with a lower ranked letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Several Greek letters are used as phonetic symbols in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Several of them denote fricative consonants; the rest stand for variants of vowel sounds.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The symbol in Americanist phonetic notation for the voiceless alveolar lateral fricative is the Greek letter lambda ⟨λ⟩, but ⟨ɬ⟩ in the IPA.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The IPA symbol for the palatal lateral approximant is ⟨ʎ⟩, which looks similar to lambda, but is actually an inverted lowercase *y*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Greek letters were also used to write numbers.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In the classical Ionian system, the first nine letters of the alphabet stood for the numbers from 1 to 9, the next nine letters stood for the multiples of 10, from 10 to 90, and the next nine letters stood for the multiples of 100, from 100 to 900.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] For this purpose, in addition to the 24 letters which by that time made up the standard alphabet, three otherwise obsolete letters were retained or revived: digamma ⟨Ϝ⟩ for 6, koppa ⟨Ϙ⟩ for 90, and a rare Ionian letter for [ss], today called sampi ⟨Ͳ⟩, for 900.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This system has remained in use in Greek up to the present day, although today it is only employed for limited purposes such as enumerating chapters in a book, similar to the way Roman numerals are used in English.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The three extra symbols are today written as ⟨ϛ⟩, ⟨ϟ⟩ and ⟨ϡ⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] To mark a letter as a numeral sign, a small stroke called *keraia* is added to the right of it.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In North America, many college fraternities and sororities are named with combinations of Greek letters, and are hence also known as "Greek letter organizations".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] This naming tradition was initiated by the foundation of the Phi Beta Kappa society at the College of William and Mary in 1776.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The name of this fraternal organization is an acronym for the ancient Greek phrase Φιλοσοφία Βίου Κυβερνήτης (*Philosophia Biou Kybernētēs*), which means "Love of wisdom, the guide of life" and serves as the organization's motto.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Sometimes early fraternal organizations were known by their Greek letter names because the mottos that these names stood for were secret and revealed only to members of the fraternity.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Different chapters within the same fraternity are almost always (with a handful of exceptions) designated using Greek letters as serial numbers.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The founding chapter of each organization is its A chapter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] As an organization expands, it establishes a B chapter, a Γ chapter, and so on and so forth.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] In an organization that expands to more than 24 chapters, the chapter after Ω chapter is AA chapter, followed by AB chapter, etc.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Each of these is still a "chapter Letter", albeit a double-digit letter just as 10 through 99 are double-digit numbers.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] The Roman alphabet has a similar extended form with such double-digit letters when necessary, but it is used for columns in a table or chart rather than chapters of an organization.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] Some letters can occur in variant shapes, mostly inherited from medieval minuscule handwriting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p01] While their use in normal typography of Greek is purely a matter of font styles, some such variants have been given separate encodings in Unicode.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] For computer usage, a variety of encodings have been used for Greek online, many of them documented in RFC 1947.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] The two principal ones still used today are ISO/IEC 8859-7 and Unicode.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] ISO 8859-7 supports only the monotonic orthography; Unicode supports both the monotonic and polytonic orthographies.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] For the range A0–FF (hex), it follows the Unicode range 370–3CF (see below) except that some symbols, like ©, ½, § etc. are used where Unicode has unused locations.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] Like all ISO-8859 encodings, it is equal to ASCII for 00–7F (hex).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] Unicode supports polytonic orthography well enough for ordinary continuous text in modern and ancient Greek, and even many archaic forms for epigraphy.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] With the use of combining characters, Unicode also supports Greek philology and dialectology and various other specialized requirements.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] Most current text rendering engines do not render diacritics well, so, though alpha with macron and acute can be *represented* as U+03B1 U+0304 U+0301, this rarely renders well: ᾱ́.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] There are two main blocks of Greek characters in Unicode.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] The first is "Greek and Coptic" (U+0370 to U+03FF).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] This block is based on ISO 8859-7 and is sufficient to write Modern Greek.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] There are also some archaic letters and Greek-based technical symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] This block also supports the Coptic alphabet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] Formerly, most Coptic letters shared codepoints with similar-looking Greek letters; but in many scholarly works, both scripts occur, with quite different letter shapes, so as of Unicode 4.1, Coptic and Greek were disunified.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] Those Coptic letters with no Greek equivalents still remain in this block (U+03E2 to U+03EF).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] To write polytonic Greek, one may use combining diacritical marks or the precomposed characters in the "Greek Extended" block (U+1F00 to U+1FFF).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/greek-alphabet-p02] IBM code pages 437, 860, 861, 862, 863, and 865 contain the letters ΓΘΣΦΩαδεπστφ (plus β as an alternative interpretation for ß).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In writing and typography, a **ligature** is the combination two or more graphemes or letters into one glyph.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The ampersand ⟨&⟩ symbol developed from a ligature that combined the handwritten Latin letters *e* and *t* (spelling *et*, Latin for *and*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The earliest known script Sumerian cuneiform and Egyptian hieratic both include many cases of character combinations that gradually evolve from ligatures into separately recognizable characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Other notable ligatures, such as the Brahmic abugidas and the Germanic bind rune, figure prominently throughout ancient manuscripts.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] These new glyphs emerge alongside the proliferation of writing with a stylus, whether on paper or clay, and often for a practical reason: faster handwriting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Merchants especially needed a way to speed up the process of written communication and found that conjoining letters and abbreviating words for lay use was more convenient for record keeping and transaction than the bulky long forms.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Around the 9th and 10th centuries, monasteries became a fountainhead for these types of script modifications.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Medieval scribes who wrote in Latin increased their writing speed by combining characters and by introducing notational abbreviations.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Others conjoined letters for aesthetic purposes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] For example, in blackletter, letters with right-facing bowls (⟨b⟩, ⟨o⟩, and ⟨p⟩) and those with left-facing bowls (⟨c⟩, ⟨e⟩, ⟨o⟩, ⟨d⟩, ⟨g⟩ and ⟨q⟩) were written with the facing edges of the bowls superimposed.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In many script forms, characters such as ⟨h⟩, ⟨m⟩, and ⟨n⟩ had their vertical strokes superimposed.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Scribes also used notational abbreviations to avoid having to write a whole character in one stroke.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Manuscripts in the fourteenth century employed hundreds of such abbreviations.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In handwriting, a ligature is made by joining two or more characters in an atypical fashion by merging their parts, or by writing one above or inside the other.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In printing, a ligature is a group of characters that is typeset as a unit, so the characters do not have to be joined.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] For example, in some cases the ⟨fi⟩ ligature prints the letters ⟨f⟩ and ⟨i⟩ with a greater separation than when they are typeset as separate letters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] When printing with movable type was invented around 1450, typefaces included many ligatures and additional letters, as they were based on handwriting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligatures made printing with movable type easier because one sort would replace frequent combinations of letters and also allowed more complex and interesting character designs which would otherwise collide with one another.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Because of their complexity, ligatures began to fall out of use in the 20th century.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Sans serif typefaces, increasingly used for body text, generally avoid ligatures, though notable exceptions include Gill Sans and Futura.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Inexpensive phototypesetting machines in the 1970s (which did not require journeyman knowledge or training to operate) also generally avoid them.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A few, however, became characters in their own right, see below the sections about German ß, various Latin accented letters, & et al.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The trend against digraph use was further strengthened by the desktop publishing revolution.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Early computer software in particular had no way to allow for ligature substitution (the automatic use of ligatures where appropriate), while most new digital typefaces did not include ligatures.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] As most of the early PC development was designed for the English language (which already treated ligatures as optional at best) dependence on ligatures did not carry over to digital.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligature use fell as the number of traditional hand compositors and hot metal typesetting machine operators dropped because of the mass production of the IBM Selectric brand of electric typewriter in 1961.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligatures have grown in popularity in the 21st century because of an increasing interest in creating typesetting systems that evoke arcane designs and classical scripts.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] One of the first computer typesetting programs to take advantage of computer-driven typesetting (and later laser printers) was Donald Knuth's TeX program.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Now the standard method of mathematical typesetting, its default fonts are explicitly based on nineteenth-century styles.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Many new fonts feature extensive ligature sets; these include FF Scala, Seria and others by Martin Majoor and Hoefler Text by Jonathan Hoefler.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Mrs Eaves by Zuzana Licko contains a particularly large set to allow designers to create dramatic display text with a feel of antiquity.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A parallel use of ligatures is seen in the creation of script fonts that join letterforms to simulate handwriting effectively.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This trend is caused in part by the increased support for other languages and alphabets in modern computing, many of which use ligatures somewhat extensively.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This has caused the development of new digital typesetting techniques such as OpenType, and the incorporation of ligature support into the text display systems of macOS, Windows, and applications like Microsoft Office.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] An increasing modern trend is to use a "Th" ligature which reduces spacing between these letters to make it easier to read, a trait infrequent in metal type.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Today, modern font programming divides ligatures into three groups, which can be activated separately: standard, contextual and historical.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Standard ligatures are needed to allow the font to display without errors such as character collision.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Designers sometimes find contextual and historic ligatures desirable for creating effects or to evoke an old-fashioned print look.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligatures are also used for logo creation, such as the Bluetooth logo, (a ligature merging the runes (ᚼ, Hagall) and (ᛒ, Bjarkan)).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Many ligatures combine ⟨f⟩ with the following letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A particularly prominent example is ⟨ﬁ⟩ (or ⟨f‌i⟩, rendered with two normal letters).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The tittle of the ⟨i⟩ in many typefaces collides with the hood of the ⟨f⟩ when placed beside each other in a word, and are combined into a single glyph with the tittle absorbed into the ⟨f⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Linotype, ligature matrices for ⟨fa⟩, ⟨fe⟩, ⟨fo⟩, ⟨fr⟩, ⟨fs⟩, ⟨ft⟩, ⟨fb⟩, ⟨fh⟩, ⟨fu⟩, ⟨fy⟩, and for ⟨f⟩ followed by a full stop, comma, or hyphen are optional in many typefaces, as well as the equivalent set for the doubled ⟨ff⟩, as a method to overcome the machine's physical restrictions.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] These arose because with the usual type sort for lowercase ⟨f⟩, the end of its hood is on a kern, which would be damaged by collision with raised parts of the next letter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligatures crossing the morpheme boundary of a composite word are sometimes considered incorrect, especially in official German orthography as outlined in the *Duden*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] An English example of this would be ⟨ff⟩ in *shelf‌ful*; a German example would be *Schiff‌fahrt* ("boat trip").
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Some computer programs (such as TeX) provide a setting to disable ligatures for German, while some users have also written macros to identify which ligatures to disable.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Turkish distinguishes dotted and dotless "I".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] If a ligature with *f* were to be used in words such as *fırın* [oven] and *fikir* [idea], this contrast would be obscured.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The ⟨fi⟩ ligature, at least in the form typical to other languages, is therefore not used in Turkish typesetting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Conversely, the "sz" ligature has merged into a single character, the German ß (see below).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Sometimes, ligatures for ⟨st⟩ (⟨ﬆ⟩), ⟨ſt⟩ (⟨ﬅ⟩), ⟨ch⟩, ⟨ck⟩, ⟨ct⟩, ⟨Qu⟩ and ⟨Th⟩ are used (e.g. in the typeface Linux Libertine).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Besides conventional ligatures, in the metal type era some newspapers commissioned custom condensed single sorts for the names of common long names that might appear in news headings, such as "Eisenhower", "Chamberlain".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In these cases the characters did not appear combined, just more tightly spaced than if printed conventionally.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The German letter ⟨ß⟩ (*Eszett*, also called the *scharfes S*, meaning *sharp s*) is an official letter of the alphabet in Germany and Austria.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A recognizable ligature representing the ⟨sz⟩ digraph develops in handwriting in the early 14th century.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Its name *Es-zett* (meaning S-Z) suggests a connection of "long s and z" (ſʒ) but the Latin script also knows a ligature of "long s over round s" (ſs).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Since German was mostly set in blackletter typefaces until the 1940s, and those typefaces were rarely set in uppercase, a capital version of the *Eszett* never came into common use, even though its creation has been discussed since the end of the 19th century.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Therefore, the common replacement in uppercase typesetting was originally SZ (*Maße* "measure" → *MAS‌ZE*, different from *Mas‌se* "mass" → *MAS‌SE*) and later SS (*Maße* → *MAS‌SE*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Until 2017, the SS replacement was the only valid spelling according to the official orthography in Germany and Austria.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Switzerland, the ß is omitted altogether in favour of ss.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The capital version (ẞ) of the Eszett character has occasionally been used since 1905/06, has been part of Unicode since 2008, and has appeared in more and more typefaces.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Since the end of 2010, the *Ständiger Ausschuss für geographische Namen (StAGN)* has suggested the new upper case character for "ß" rather than replacing it with "SS" or "SZ" for geographical names.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A new standardized German keyboard layout (DIN 2137-T2) has included the capital ß since 2012.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The new character entered the official orthographic rules in June 2017.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] For example, compare the colonial-era spelling *seepꝏash* with the modern Wôpanâak Language Reclamation Project (WLRP) spelling *seep8ash*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] As the letter ⟨W⟩ is an addition to the Latin alphabet that originated in the seventh century, the phoneme it represents was formerly written in various ways.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Old English, the runic letter wynn ⟨Ƿ⟩ was used, but Norman influence forced wynn out of use.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] By the 14th century, the "new" letter ⟨W⟩, originated as two ⟨V⟩ glyphs or ⟨U⟩ glyphs joined, developed into a legitimate letter with its own position in the alphabet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Because of its relative youth compared to other letters of the alphabet, only a few European languages (including Breton, Dutch, English, German, Maltese, Polish, Walloon, and Welsh) use the letter in native words.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The character ⟨Æ⟩ (lower case ⟨æ⟩; in ancient times named *æsc*) when used in Danish, Norwegian, Icelandic, or Old English is not a typographic ligature.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It is a distinct letter — a vowel — and when collated, may be given a different place in the alphabetical order than Ae.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In modern English orthography, ⟨Æ⟩ is not considered an independent letter but a spelling variant, for example: "encyclopædia" versus "encyclopaedia" or "encyclopedia".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In this use, ⟨Æ⟩ comes from Medieval Latin, where it was an optional ligature in some specific words that had been transliterated and borrowed from Ancient Greek, for example, "Æneas".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It is still found as a variant in English and French words descended or borrowed from Medieval Latin, but the trend has recently been towards printing the ⟨A⟩ and ⟨E⟩ separately.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Similarly, ⟨Œ⟩ and ⟨œ⟩, while normally printed as ligatures in French, are replaced by component letters if technical restrictions require it.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The letter hwair ⟨ƕ⟩, used only in transliteration of the Gothic language, resembles a ⟨hw⟩ ligature.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It was introduced by philologists around 1900 to replace the digraph ⟨hv⟩ formerly used to express the phoneme in question, e.g. by Migne in the 1860s (*Patrologia Latina* vol.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The Byzantines had a unique o-u ligature ⟨Ȣ⟩ that, while originally based on the Greek alphabet's ο-υ, carried over into Latin alphabets as well.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This ligature is still seen today on icon artwork in Greek Orthodox churches, and sometimes in graffiti or other forms of informal or decorative writing.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Gha ⟨ƣ⟩, a rarely used letter based on Q, was misconstrued by the ISO to be an OI ligature because of its appearance, and is thus permanently named in Unicode as "Oi", though that has been amended with a correction.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Historically, it was used in many Latin-based orthographies of Turkic (e.g., Azerbaijani) and other central Asian languages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The International Phonetic Alphabet formerly used ligatures to represent affricate consonants, of which six are encoded in Unicode: ʣ, ʤ, ʥ, ʦ, ʧ and ʨ.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] One fricative consonant is still represented with a ligature: ɮ, and the extensions to the IPA contain three more: ʩ, ʪ and ʫ.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The Initial Teaching Alphabet, a short-lived alphabet intended for young children, used a number of ligatures to represent long vowels: ⟨æ⟩, ⟨ꜷ⟩, ⟨œ⟩, ⟨ᵫ⟩, and ligatures for ⟨ϵϵ⟩, ⟨ie⟩, ⟨oi⟩, and ⟨ou⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Ligatures for consonants also existed, including ligatures of ⟨ʗh⟩, ⟨ʃh⟩, ⟨ʈh⟩, ⟨th⟩, and ⟨wh⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The ligatures were approved in 2025 for publication in Unicode 18.0.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The most common ligature in modern usage is the ampersand ⟨&⟩ .
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This was originally a ligature of ⟨E⟩ and ⟨t⟩ , forming the Latin: *et*, meaning *and*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It has exactly the same use in French and in English.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The ampersand comes in many different forms.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Because of its ubiquity, it is generally no longer considered a ligature, but a logogram.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Like many other ligatures, it has at times been considered a letter (e.g., in early Modern English); in English it is pronounced *and*, not *et*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In most typefaces, it does not immediately resemble the two letters used to form it, although certain typefaces use designs in the form of a ligature (examples include the original versions of Futura and Univers, Trebuchet MS, and Civilité, known in modern times as the italic of Garamond).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Similarly, the number sign ⟨#⟩ originated as a stylized abbreviation of the Roman term *libra pondo*, written as ⟨℔⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Over time, the number sign was simplified to how it is seen today, with two horizontal strokes across two slash-like strokes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Now a logogram, the symbol is used mainly to denote (in the US) numbers, and weight in pounds.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It has also been used popularly on push-button telephones and as the hashtag indicator.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The at sign ⟨@⟩ is possibly a ligature, but there are many different theories about the origin.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] One theory says that the French word *à* (meaning *at*), was simplified by scribes who, instead of lifting the pen to write the grave accent, drew an arc around the ⟨a⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Another states that it is short for the Latin word for *toward*, *ad*, with the ⟨d⟩ being represented by the arc.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Another says it is short for an abbreviation of the term *each at*, with the ⟨e⟩ encasing the ⟨a⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Around the 18th century, it started being used in commerce to indicate price per unit, as "15 units @ $1".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] After the popularization of Email, this fairly unpopular character became widely known, used to tag specific users.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Lately, it has been used to de-gender nouns in Spanish with no agreed pronunciation.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The dollar sign ⟨$⟩ possibly originated as a ligature (for "pesos", although there are other theories as well) but is now a logogram.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] At least once, the United States dollar used a symbol resembling an overlapping U-S ligature, with the right vertical bar of the U intersecting through the middle of the S ( US ) to resemble the modern dollar sign.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The Spanish peseta was sometimes abbreviated by a ligature ⟨₧⟩ (from *Pts*).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The ligature ⟨₣⟩ (F-with-bar, from *Fr*) was proposed in 1968 by Édouard Balladur, Minister of Economy. as a symbol for the French franc but was never adopted nor officially used before its replacement with the euro in 2002.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In astronomy, the planetary symbol for Mercury (☿) may be a ligature of Mercury's caduceus and a cross (which was added in the 16th century to Christianize the pagan symbol), though other sources disagree; the symbol for Venus ♀ may be a ligature of the Greek letters ⟨ϕ⟩ (phi) and ⟨κ⟩ (kappa).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The symbol for Jupiter (♃) descends from a Greek zeta with a horizontal stroke, ⟨Ƶ⟩, as an abbreviation for *Zeus*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Saturn's astronomical symbol (♄) has been traced back to the Greek Oxyrhynchus Papyri, where it can be seen to be a Greek kappa-rho with a horizontal stroke, as an abbreviation for Κρονος (Cronus), the Greek name for the planet.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] It later came to look like a lower-case Greek eta, with the cross added at the top in the 16th century to Christianize it.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The dwarf planet Pluto is symbolized by a PL ligature, ♇.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] A different PL ligature, ⅊, represents the property line in surveying.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In engineering diagrams, a CL ligature, ℄, represents the center line of an object.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The interrobang ⟨‽⟩ is an unconventional punctuation meant to combine the interrogation point (or the question mark) and the bang (printer's slang for exclamation mark) into one symbol, used to denote a sentence which is both a question and is exclaimed.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] For example, the sentence "Is that actually true‽" shows that the speaker is surprised while asking their question.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Alchemy used a set of mostly standardized symbols, many of which were ligatures: 🜇 (AR, for aqua regia); 🜈 (S inside a V, for aqua vitae); 🝫 (MB, for *balneum Mariae* [Mary's bath], a double boiler); 🝬 (VB, for *balneum vaporis*, a steam bath); and 🝛 (*aaa* with overline, for amalgam).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Composer Arnold Schoenberg introduced two ligatures as musical symbols to denote melody and countermelody.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The symbols are ligatures of HT and NT, 𝆦 and 𝆧, from the German for hauptstimme and nebenstimme respectively.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Digraphs, such as ⟨ll⟩ in Spanish or Welsh, are not ligatures in the general case as the two letters are displayed as separate glyphs: although written together, when they are joined in handwriting or italic fonts the base form of the letters is not changed and the individual glyphs remain separate.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Like some ligatures discussed above, these digraphs may or may not be considered individual letters in their respective languages.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Until the 1994 spelling reform, the digraphs ⟨ch⟩ and ⟨ll⟩ were considered separate letters in Spanish for collation purposes.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Catalan makes a difference between "Spanish ll" or palatalized l, written *ll* as in *llei* (law), and "French ll" or geminated l, written *l·l* as in *col·lega* (colleague).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The difference can be illustrated with the French digraph *œu*, which is composed of the ligature *œ* and the simplex letter *u*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Dutch, ⟨ĳ⟩ can be considered a digraph, a ligature, or a letter in itself, depending on the standard used.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Its uppercase and lowercase forms are often available as a single glyph with a distinctive ligature in several professional typefaces (e.g.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Sans serif uppercase ⟨Ĳ⟩ glyphs, popular in the Netherlands, typically use a ligature resembling a ⟨U⟩ with a broken left-hand stroke.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Adding to the confusion, Dutch handwriting can render ⟨y⟩ (which is not found in native Dutch words, but occurs in words borrowed from other languages) as a ⟨ĳ⟩-glyph without the dots in its lowercase form and the ⟨Ĳ⟩ in its uppercase form looking virtually identical (only slightly bigger).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] When written as two separate letters, both should be capitalized – or both not – to form a correctly spelled word, like *IJs* or *ijs* (ice).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Written Chinese has a long history of creating new characters by merging parts or wholes of other Chinese characters.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] However, a few of these combinations do not represent morphemes but retain the original multi-character (multiple morpheme) reading and are therefore not considered true characters themselves.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Chinese, these ligatures are called *héwén* (合文) or *héshū* (合書); see polysyllabic Chinese characters for more.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] One popular ligature used on *chūntiē* decorations used for Chinese Lunar New Year is "(⿱𡩧⿺進⿰貝招)" a combination of the four characters for *zhāocái jìnbǎo* (招財進寶), meaning "ushering in wealth and fortune" and used as a popular New Year's greeting.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In 1924, Du Dingyou (杜定友; 1898–1967) created the ligature 圕 from two of the three characters 圖書館 (*túshūguǎn*), meaning "library".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Although it does have an assigned pronunciation of *tuān* and appears in many dictionaries, it is not a morpheme and cannot be used as such in Chinese.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Instead, it is usually considered a graphic representation of *túshūguǎn*.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Similar to the ligatures were several "two-syllable Chinese characters" (雙音節漢字) created in the 19th century as Chinese characters for SI units.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In Chinese these units are disyllabic and standardly written with two characters, as 厘米 *límǐ* "centimeter" (厘 centi-, 米 meter) or 千瓦 *qiānwǎ* "kilowatt".
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] However, in the 19th century these were often written via compound characters, pronounced disyllabically, such as 瓩 for 千瓦 or 糎 for 厘米 – some of these characters were also used in Japan, where they were pronounced with borrowed European readings instead.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] These have now fallen out of general use, but are occasionally seen.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The CJK Compatibility Unicode block features characters that have been combined into one square character in the legacy character set so that it matches Japanese text.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] For example, the Japanese equivalent of "stock company", 株式会社 (*kabushiki gaisha*) can be represented in 1 Unicode character ⟨㍿⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Its romanized abbreviation *K.K.* can also be 1 character ⟨㏍⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] There are other Latin abbreviations such as *kg* for "kilogram" that can be ligated into 1 square character ⟨㎏⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The OpenType font format includes features for associating multiple glyphs to a single character, used for ligature substitution.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Typesetting software may or may not implement this feature, even if it is explicitly present in the font's metadata.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] XeTeX is a TeX typesetting engine designed to make the most of such advanced features.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This type of substitution used to be needed mainly for typesetting Arabic texts, but ligature lookups and substitutions are being put into all kinds of Western Latin OpenType fonts.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] In OpenType, there are standard `liga`, historical `hlig`, contextual `clig`, discretionary `dlig` and required `rlig` ligatures.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Opinion is divided over whether it is the job of writers or typesetters to decide where to use ligatures.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] TeX is an example of a computer typesetting system that makes use of ligatures automatically.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The Computer Modern Roman typeface provided with TeX includes the five common ligatures ⟨ff⟩, ⟨fi⟩, ⟨fl⟩, ⟨ffi⟩, and ⟨ffl⟩.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] When TeX finds these combinations in a text, it substitutes the appropriate ligature, unless overridden by the typesetter.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] CSS3 provides control over these properties using `font-feature-settings`, though the CSS Fonts Module Level 4 draft standard indicates that authors should prefer several other properties.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Those include `font-variant-ligatures`, `common-ligatures`, `discretionary-ligatures`, `historical-ligatures`, and `contextual`.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] This table below shows discrete letter pairs on the left, the corresponding Unicode ligature in the middle column, and the Unicode code point on the right.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Provided you are using an operating system and browser that can handle Unicode, and have the correct Unicode fonts installed, some or all of these will display correctly.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] (Unicode has continued to add ligatures, but only in such cases that the ligatures were used as distinct letters in a language or could be interpreted as standalone symbols.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Microsoft Word disables ligature substitution by default, largely for backward compatibility when editing documents created in earlier versions of Word.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Users can enable automatic ligature substitution on the Advanced tab of the Font dialog box.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] The Medieval Unicode Font Initiative includes encodings for ligatures not yet deemed worthy to be included in Unicode; its prescribed code points for such ligatures are located in the Private Use Areas.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] There are separate code points for the digraph DZ, the Dutch digraph IJ, and for the Serbo-Croatian digraphs DŽ, LJ, and NJ.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Although similar, these are digraphs, not ligatures.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Four "ligature ornaments" are included from U+1F670 to U+1F673 in the Ornamental Dingbats block: regular and bold variants of ℯT (script e and T) and of ɛT (open E and T).
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Typographic ligatures are used in a form of contemporary art, as can be illustrated by Chinese artist Xu Bing's work in which he combines Latin letters to form characters that resemble Chinese.
[src:1979-vuelta-a-espana/typographic-ligature] Croatian designer Maja Škripelj also created a ligature that combined Glagolitic letters ⰘⰓ for euro coins.
